Correspondence to: Q.‐H. Zhang, zhangqinghe@sdu.edu.cn

Polar Ionospheric Large‐Scale Structures and Dynamics Revealed by TEC Keogram Extracted From TEC Maps
Y. Wang1,2, Q.‐H. Zhang1, Y.‐Z. Ma1, P. T. Jayachandran2, Z.‐Y. Xing1, N. Balan1, and S.‐R. Zhang3
1Shandong Provincial Key Laboratory of Optical Astronomy and Solar‐Terrestrial Environment, Institute of Space Sciences, Shandong University, Weihai, China, 2Physics Department, University of New Brunswick, Fredericton, New Brunswick, Canada, 3Haystack Observatory, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Westford, MA, USA
Abstract A method named total electron content (TEC) keogram is introduced for surveying the
large‐scale irregularities continuously in the polar ionosphere. The TEC keogram is developed from a movie of TEC maps along various meridian lines from the dayside to the nightside across the magnetic pole, trying to identify and track several types of ionospheric structures. Through two examples, a clear train of polar cap patches are identiﬁed from TEC keogram and conﬁrmed by SuperDARN radar observations. The motion speed of these patches estimated from this tool agrees with SuperDARN radar measurements. Then, the motions of patches relative to the background convection through the whole polar cap are statistically studied for the ﬁrst time. Moreover, the occurrence dependence of fully tracked patches on months, UT hours, and interplanetary magnetic ﬁeld conditions is generally consistent with previous reports. These results suggest that the TEC keogram offers a power tool for continuous monitoring and studying of large‐scale plasma irregularities in the polar ionosphere.

Citation: Wang, Y., Zhang, Q.‐H., Ma, Y.‐Z., Jayachandran, P. T., Xing, Z.‐Y., Balan, N., & Zhang, S.‐R. (2020). Polar ionospheric large‐scale structures and dynamics revealed by TEC keogram extracted from TEC maps. Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics, 125, e2019JA027020. https://doi.org/ 10.1029/2019JA027020 Received 9 JUN 2019 Accepted 25 DEC 2019 Accepted article online 30 DEC 2019
©2019. American Geophysical Union. All Rights Reserved.

1. Introduction
The conjugate polar ionospheres are highly dynamic regions where geomagnetic ﬁeld lines are nearly vertically upward and downward and possibly connecting to the outer space directly. They are therefore considered as key regions in the solar‐terrestrial energy coupling system. Due to the frequent intrusion of particles and energy from solar wind through the interplanetary magnetic ﬁeld (IMF), large number of high‐density structures are often generated in this region. The density structures include storm enhanced density (SED; e.g., Foster, 1993; Foster & Rideout, 2007; Zou et al., 2013, 2014; Thomas et al., 2013), tongue of ionization (e.g., Foster et al., 2005; ), and polar cap patches (e.g., Carlson et al., 2004; Crowley, 1996; Lorentzen et al., 2010; Zhang, Zhang, Lockwood, et al., 2013). SED is a plume of very high density plasma around the noon sector. It usually extends from lower latitudes to higher latitudes in the afternoon sunlit sector, possibly enters into the polar cap, and ﬁnally develops into tongue of ionizations or patches (e.g., Foster, 2008). Polar cap patches are deﬁned as large‐scale (approximately hundreds to thousands of kilometers) plasma structures of density 2 or more times greater compared to the surrounding region in the polar cap. The patches move along antisunward directions and follow dynamic convection patterns (e.g., Carlson, 2012; Moen et al., 2013; Oksavik et al., 2006, 2010; Zhang et al., 2011, 2015; Zhang, Zhang, Lockwood, et al., 2013). In technological applications, the large‐scale plasma irregularities often degrade the applications of Global Navigation Satellite System especially when combined with simultaneous particle precipitation (e.g., Jin et al., 2014, 2016; Moen et al., 2013; Oksavik et al., 2015).
In order to mitigate the above‐mentioned negative effect, a large number of instruments have been put into service to investigate the various structures in the polar ionosphere. Recently, measurement of total electron content (TEC) has become a very popular tool due to its capability of continuous monitoring and global coverage (e.g., Foster, 1993; Foster et al., 2005; Oksavik et al., 2006; Pi et al., 1997; Prikryl et al., 2016; Thomas et al., 2013; Zhang et al., 2017; Zhang, Zhang, Lockwood, et al., 2013; Zhang, Zhang, Moen, et al., 2013; Zou et al., 2013). For example, Pi et al. (1997) created the ﬁrst global maps of the irregularities. Following this, Zhang, Zhang, Lockwood, et al. (2013) reported the full cycle of convection ﬂow by tracking the movement of polar cap patches from a time series of TEC maps. By using the TEC maps, the large‐scale structures were identiﬁed and their scintillation behaviors were unveiled (e.g., Wang et al., 2016). The statistical ratios of patch‐to‐background density were also obtained from the plentiful of TEC maps, which help identifying

WANG ET AL.

1 of 11

Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics

10.1029/2019JA027020

the possible mechanisms of the patch formation (e.g., David et al., 2016). The TEC map has thus become a popular and useful tool.
In order to exploit the potential of TEC maps, a powerful method named TEC keogram is developed from a time series of TEC maps for investigating the polar ionosphere. This paper describes the methodology of creating the TEC keogram. The paper also validates the TEC keogram by using it for successfully capturing the large‐scale plasma structures in the polar ionosphere. Two case studies are presented comparing TEC keograms with their original TEC maps, as well as with SuperDARN radar observations. The speed of movement of the polar cap patches on average is also estimated using the TEC keogram. In addition, the dependence of the patch occurrence on months, UT hours, and IMF conditions is investigated in detail. It will be shown that the TEC keogram is a powerful tool for investigating the high‐latitude ionosphere.

2. Methodology of TEC Keogram

