In this section, we brieﬂy describe the method of developing the TEC keogram from TEC maps.
2.1. The TEC Map

nightside are, respectively, highlighted by magenta solid circle, magenta dashed circle, black dashed circle, yellow dashed curve, and black dashed curve.

The TEC data are usually obtained by measuring the dispersion of the satellite signal passing through the ionosphere by ground‐based dual‐ frequency receivers. The slant TEC data therefore contain the integrated

electron content along the line of sight from the receiver to the satellite.

In the process of obtaining the slant TEC data, the measurement errors involving the biases due to

pseudo‐range and initial (or raw) phase of the signal transmitted by satellites are removed, calibrated, and

quality controlled. The slant line‐of‐sight TECS can be converted to the equivalent vertical TECV by multiplying TECS by a function containing cosθ of the angle θ between the line‐of‐sight and vertical directions.

We obtained the vertical TEC data from the madrigal online database (http://www.openmadrigal.org/), which were collected from the global network of ground receivers and processed by the MIT Automated Processing of GPS software (Rideout & Coster, 2006; Vierinen et al., 2015). At present, the number of ground receivers is greater than 5,000, providing a dense enough global coverage even in the arctic. The TEC data are binned into the grids of spatial size 1° geographic latitude × 1° geographic longitude at 5‐min time resolution (Figure S1 in the supporting information). For the present purpose of focusing on the arctic, the TEC maps can be used since 2011. The TEC data are projected on the Altitude Adjustment Corrected Geomagnetic coordinates.

Figure 1 presents an example of the TEC map in magnetic latitude (MLat) and magnetic local time (MLT) grids around 10:07 UT on 16 March 2016, where the noon is at the top and dusk is on the left, in which the MLat is shown from 50° with an interval of 10°. The white areas are TEC data gaps. For improving the performance of these maps, a median‐ﬁltering method of smoothing techniques is applied to ﬁll the small data gaps. Note that the solar wind and IMF conditions on this day are mentioned in section 3. It may be noted that Figure S1 shows the TEC data before applying this improvement technique. As shown in Figure 1, several types of plasma structures can be identiﬁed in terms of TEC values. The plasma structures include highest TEC in the dayside sunlit region, pole with the lowest TEC, auroral oval with relatively higher TEC in lower MLat than in the polar cap, and midlatitude trough in the nightside around 50° MLat extending from 20:00 MLT to 06:00 MLT. A SED is marked by the solid magenta circle around the noon sector, probably created by the combined effect of ionospheric rotation and convection pattern. In the middle of the dial, the ﬁne black dotted curve suggests the day‐night terminator. Further, looking at the meridian TEC line of 12–0 MLT from the dayside solar illuminated region to nightside lower latitude, several kinds of large‐scale structures appear in sequence, consisting of the SED (magenta solid circle), polar cap patch (magenta dashed circle), polar cap (black dashed circle), auroral oval (above yellow dashed curve), and midlatitude trough (over black thick dashed curve). If one puts a time series of such TEC lines in sequence, the resulting schematic diagram would illustrate the potential of making a method (or the TEC

