keogram) to monitor the evolution of the polar ionosphere, instead of skimming into too many individual TEC maps.

Figure 2. The MLat/MLT coordinate frame of TEC maps with spatial size of 2° MLat × 00:08 MLT. Three meridian TEC lines along 12–0 MLT (red), 15–3 MLT (magenta), and 9–21 MLT (blue) are outlined by the color strips from (top) dayside to (bottom) nightside above 50° MLat. These TEC lines are discussed in section 2.2.

2.2. TEC Keogram Frame
Figure 2 illustrates the MLat/MLT basic coordinate frame of grid size 2° MLat × 00:08 MLT adopted for the TEC keogram development. In this dial, the evenly distributed black circles represent MLat at interval of 2° in the 50°–90° range in the northern hemisphere as marked on the right‐hand side. In this map, the lines radiating from the center indicate MLTs, which are noted by the colored numbers outside. In Figure 2, the three strips colored in red, magenta, and blue, respectively, correspond to the TEC lines at 12–0 MLT, 15–3 MLT, and 9–21 MLT. To improve the appearance of the TEC lines, these strips are extended in MLT and then averaged. Following this method, three TEC lines in different directions can be extracted from a TEC map, which is inspired by the widely used auroral keogram (e.g., Hosokawa, Kashimoto, et al., 2009; Hosokawa, Shiokawa, et al., 2009; Jin et al., 2014). Extending this method, when we use a time series of TEC lines in the three directions together, the TEC keogram is developed, which can be used to identify and continuously track the motion of large‐scale structures in the polar ionosphere. Note that the speciﬁc directions of these TEC lines are deliberately determined to follow the dynamics of the convection pattern better.

3. TEC Keogram
This section presents two case studies to describe the capability of TEC keogram, which are, respectively, carried out through comparisons with the corresponding original TEC maps and SuperDARN Rankin Inlet (RKN) radar observations.
3.1. Solar Wind Parameters
The solar wind and IMF data and geomagnetic indices are available on the OMNI‐2 website (https://omniweb.gsfc.nasa.gov/html/HROdocum.html#1a); the data have been obtained from ACE and Wind satellite measurements (King & Papitashvili, 2005). On 14 March 2016, a possible magnetic cloud with signiﬁcant solar wind and IMF ﬂuctuations struck the dayside magnetopause at ~17:20 UT, making a moderate geomagnetic storm (not shown here). The time period of our interest falls in the recovery phase of this storm. Figure 3 shows an overview of the IMF By and Bz components, solar wind dynamic pressure PDyn, geomagnetic indices AU/AL, and SYM‐H during 06:00–21:00 UT on 16 March 2016. The IMF and solar wind parameters are time shifted by 7 min for the bow shock nose to dayside magnetopause distance. During the interval of interest, the solar wind and IMF conditions are highly disturbed. In Figure 3a, the shaded period emphasizes a time interval of 13:30–17:45 UT. During this interval, the IMF Bz is almost positive (northward) with slight short excursions below 0 nT at around 14:15 UT. Before this interval, the IMF Bz was generally negative (southward) with several peaks up to −5 nT. After this interval, beginning at 17:45 UT, IMF Bz turned steadily southward. The direction of IMF Bz determines the dayside reconnection rate, negative for preference and positive for suppression. Meanwhile, the IMF By component is always negative, except for a few weak positive excursions, potentially indicating the rotation of the convection pattern. The PDyn ﬂuctuates but does not exceed above 4 nPa (Figure 3b). The AU/AL indices undergo gradual ﬂuctuations and reach 1,000/−1,000 nT at around 21:00 UT (Figure 3c), suggesting a possible substorm occurred. As shown in Figure 3d, the SYM‐H index wanders around −25 nT, illustrating the recovery phase of a magnetic storm. The time between the two of vertical red dashed lines in Figure 3 corresponds to the time interval of interest in section 3.2.
3.2. Large‐Scale Structures
Figure 4 summarizes the TEC maps on MLat/MLT grids at selected times. Figures 4a and 4f include the convection patterns obtained from SuperDARN radars (Chisham et al., 2007; Greenwald et al., 1995; Ruohoniemi & Baker, 1998). The convection patterns are usually interpreted as black closed curves (solid

