for negative equivalent potential and dashed for positive potential), referring to plasma drift from noon sector to nightside along antisunward direction in the polar cap and then return back in both morning/afternoon cells. On the right‐hand side of each panel, there is a color bar representing TEC scale of 0–16 TECu (1 TECu = 1016 ele/m2).
In Figure 4, at least four types of large‐scale structures are identiﬁed by the TEC values and density gradients associated with the convection pattern, consisting of SEDs, polar cap patches, middle‐latitude trough, and contracted auroral oval. In Figures 4a–4c, the SED (solid magenta circle) with high‐density plasma (~12 TECu) drifts from the low‐latitude afternoon sector to high‐latitude noon sector, and enters the polar cap forming a patch. Around 13:02 UT (Figure 4c), a clear polar cap patch (solid magenta circle, ~10 TECu) is chopping off from the former SED plume (magenta dashed circle) probably by the sunward ﬂow at subauroral latitude. After the patch is created, it enters into the polar cap and moves across the pole from dayside to nightside (the solid magenta circles in Figures 4d and 4e). Meanwhile, near the segmented region, a fresh stagnant SED is formed on the noon sector. It stays around its generated region for a long time duration when TEC decreases (the magenta dashed circles in Figures 4c–4f), which is probably due to the contracted convection pattern under northward IMF Bz (please ﬁnd the IMF Bz in Figure 3a; e.g., Cowley & Lockwood, 1992; Lockwood & Carlson, 1992). Further, in Figure 4a, a clear middle‐latitude trough (region of low TEC values ~3 TECu around 52°–62° MLat) lies from the premidnight to the dawn sector, which can be inferred from the lower latitude region of the convection pattern. Comparing Figures 4a and 4f, the auroral oval contracted in less than 2 hr (see the region of sunward return ﬂow from the convection pattern). It could be possibly caused by the gradual changing of IMF Bz component from southward to weak northward (Figure 3a). Besides, as understood from the northward Bz conditions (highlighted by the shaded region in Figure 3a), this fossil SED may be lasting until the IMF Bz changes its sign. In addition, the enhanced density fragments (seen as scattering in 23–17 MLT sectors around 65°–75° MLat) are likely formed by the former polar cap patch that broke into the auroral oval and drifted by the duskside sunward return ﬂows (e.g., Figure 4a). The signiﬁcant features seen in TEC maps (Figure 4) are well captured by the TEC keogram shown in the next section.
