3.3. Results From TEC Keogram
Figure 5 shows a TEC keogram as a function of UT and MLat during 06:00–21:00 UT on 16 March 2016 (same day of the TEC map in Figure 4). The keogram is extracted from the time series of modiﬁed TEC maps in the 50°–90° MLat range along the TEC meridian lines of 12–0 MLT (Figure 5a), 15–3 MLT (Figure 5b), and 9–21 MLT (Figure 5c), respectively. The white areas are data gaps. The color bar provides the TEC scale 0–16 TECu (same as Figure 4).
In Figure 5, ﬁve clear polar cap patches are observed, which are marked by the red backslashes and labeled A–E. They almost move continuously from dayside lower latitudes to nightside lower latitudes. The black vertical dashed lines identify the time interval of the TEC map in Figure 4. During this speciﬁc period, a long‐duration SED is clearly observed (horizontal magenta dashed line; Figure 5a) at about 70° MLat on noon sector, which is consistent with the structure in Figures 4a–4f. Moreover, after being chopped off from this SED, the polar cap patch D drifts poleward and reaches the nightside, which was observed in Figures 4a– 4e. Note that the patch D is simultaneously captured by all three TEC lines (the black dashed squares in Figures 5b and 5c), when it moves across the pole. Considering the whole MLats and related time interval, the averaged cross‐cap transit speed of patch D is ~400 m/s. To further check the TEC keogram, the phenomenon of slightly enhanced density scatters in the duskside at 17–23 MLT around 70 MLat (Figures 4a–4f) is also observed in Figure 5c (black dashed oval). Comparing Figures 5a and 5c, it seems possible that these irregularities are probably created from the former patches (e.g., patches B, C, E) broken inside the auroral oval. It may be noted that the contracted auroral oval is not well captured by the TEC keogram due to the data gap.
Outside of the addressed time interval, there are several clear structures such as the patches A, B, C, and E and full SEDs. The ﬁrst sector beginning at 10:07 UT is associated with the patches B, C, and E (Figure 1). It also contains the above mentioned fossil SED until ~19:00 UT and the auroral oval in the nightside sector around 70° MLat with higher TEC values (~7 TECu) compared to the surrounding region (<4 TECu; Figure 5c). The gradually equatorward expanding auroral oval (marked by the black dashed backslash in
