4. TEC Keogram With SuperDARN Data
Figure 6 provides a good example illustrating the capability of TEC keogram when comparing with SuperDARN RKN radar. Figure 6a shows a series of TEC lines along 12–0 MLT from the TEC keogram during 12:00–24:00 UT on 17 December 2015. The black dashed frame marks the time interval of interest. Inside this frame, four clear polar cap patches move from dayside (top) to nightside (middle), which are noted by black solid backslashes. Note that outside this frame, there are several patches not marked, that is, at ~14:00 UT and ~15:00 UT and 16:30 UT and 18:00 UT. From the slopes of these lines, the average speed of cross‐cap transit of these patches are obtained (~500 m/s), which can be regarded as the mean speed of convection pattern in antisunward direction. Note that the black horizontal solid line is at 90° MLat (the magnetic pole). For comparison, the time series during 19:10–22:10 UT of the power and velocity observed by beam 7 of SuperDARN RKN radar are presented in Figures 6b and 6c, respectively, as a function of UT and MLat in the dayside. Note that the MLat scales (y axis) of Figures 6b and 6c are opposite to that of Figure 6a. The four clear poleward moving backscatter patches (mostly >30 dB) observed by the radar (Figure 6b) conﬁrm the polar cap patches detected by the TEC keogram (Figure 6). The relative locations of these enhanced density structures in the ﬁeld of view of the SuperDARN RKN radar are also indicated as black sectors in Figure S2. Within the ﬁeld of view of the radar, the beam 7 is marked by the two black solid lines. The calculated velocity of these patches (Figure 6c) is ~500 m/s in the poleward direction (red represents away from the radar), which is quiet similar to the estimated speed from the TEC keogram (Figure 6a).
