5. Statistics of Patch Occurrence
5.1. Month and UT Dependence

In the year 2015, 511 polar cap patches were manually detected from the TEC keogram, which were recorded by following these two criteria simultaneously: (1) the density of moving structures in TEC should be at least twice greater than their background and (2) these structures are fully captured from leaving the dayside segmented region to the nightside auroral oval by one TEC line. In this study, the TEC values of these structures are identiﬁed from the 12–0 MLT TEC line of TEC keogram by eyes. Their background is considered as the neighbor region outside these patches especially at the left or right side from the time series of TEC line, almost sharing the same MLat with each identiﬁed structures.

The monthly and UT distributions of these selected structures are shown in Figure 7. With months (Figure 7a), the patch occurrence follows the seasonal dependence of the ionospheric density with maxima at equinoxes (March–April and September–October) and winter‐solstice (December–February) and minimum in the summer season (May–August). Note that the unexpected low number of patches in November is due to the extremely quiet condition in this month after checking with the corresponding TEC maps. The maximum patch occurrence at equinoxes and in winter‐solstice was reported earlier (e.g., Coley & Heelis, 1998; Sojka et al., 1994). However, in Figure 7a, the number of patches at equinoxes is slightly greater than in winter‐solstice, which is not consistent with Coley and Heelis (1998) who reported that the peak was just in the winter season. Further check is required on this aspect involving much more data. Moreover, the minimum in the summer season can be explained by that during these months the background of polar cap in the northern hemisphere is much denser due to the daylight. Then, compared to other seasons, the criteria (1) is more difﬁcult to fulﬁll for selecting the structures with a density twice or greater than the background by TEC keogram.

Figure 7. The distributions of the detected 511 patches on (a) months and (b) UT hours during the whole year 2015. The patches leaving from the dayside to entering the nightside auroral oval are fully detected by TEC keogram.

In Figure 7b, the UT distribution of patches is highest in the afternoon UT sector peaking at 18–21 UT due to the inclination of the magnetic pole relative to the geographic north pole as reported earlier

