(e.g., Foster, 1993; Foster et al., 2005). This is also generally consistent with the earlier results of Sojka et al. (1994), Coley and Heelis (1998), and David et al. (2016) carried out using simulation and space/ground‐ based observations. However, an afternoon sector at 21–1 UT for the peak was reported by Ren et al. (2018), which is slightly later than our results. It may be noted that when counted from the TEC line of 12–0 MLT of TEC keogram, there are two speciﬁc regions of UT, where the statistical number of patches are inevitably smaller due to the TEC data gap in Russian sector centered at 4 UT (dayside gap) and 16 UT (nightside gap). Therefore, the number distributions in Figure 7b on the two UT regions of 2–5 UT and 13–17 UT are deﬁnitely reduced due to the TEC data gaps when following the criteria (2). For better studying the patch occurrence, a long‐term data set will be adopted to further investigate the patch occurrence on day of year and UT from a large number of increasing TEC maps.

Figure 8. The dependence of patch occurrence on IMF conditions binned in 5.2. IMF Dependence

3‐nT intervals, (a) IMF Bx, (b) IMF By, and (c) IMF Bz.

In order to discuss the possible generation mechanism of the patches, the

dependence of the patch occurrence on IMF conditions is presented. The

IMF conditions correspond to the starting time of a patch in the dayside.

The dependence of the cross‐cap transit periods of the patches on IMF conditions is investigated to deter-

mine the possible effect of IMF conditions on the moving speed of the patches (e.g., Hosokawa et al.,

2006; Hosokawa, Shiokawa, et al., 2009). Based on the statistical study above, the average cross‐cap transit

period of polar cap patches can be obtained (~2 hr), simultaneously implying their mean cross‐cap transit

speed because they were basically travelling from dayside noon sector to nightside auroral oval over a close

distance. The shorter average period corresponds to the faster moving speed. Similarly, longer period sig-

niﬁes slower moving speed.

Figure 8 presents the dependence of patch occurrences on IMF conditions binned in 3‐nT intervals, (a) for IMF Bx, (b) for IMF By, and (c) for IMF Bz. Note that the percentage scales in the three vertical axes of Figure 8 are the ratios of the patch numbers for each IMF component within 3‐nT intervals to the total number of patches in the corresponding IMF component. In Figures 8a and 8b, the patches distribute almost symmetrically centered around −3 nT, probably suggesting a symmetric contribution of IMF Bx/By on the patch formation (e.g., Hosokawa, Shiokawa, et al., 2009; Jin et al., 2019; Zhang et al., 2011). However, in Figure 8c, the distribution of patches is almost on the negative IMF Bz, indicating the signiﬁcant preference of southward IMF Bz on the transportation of patches (e.g., Hosokawa et al., 2006). These patches are actually linked to the convection pattern, which generally preferred antisunward direction under southward IMF Bz rather than under northward IMF Bz. Note that the direction of adopted TEC line of 12–0 MLT in TEC keogram is also pointing to the antisunward direction. A similar behavior of patch occurrences on IMF conditions was reported by Jin et al. (2019) with the symmetric distributions on IMF Bx and IMF By but centered on 0 nT and also preference on the negative IMF Bz. Furthermore, the southward IMF Bz has been widely reported to trigger the magnetic reconnection in the dayside magnetopause, not only driving the antisunward convection pattern but also possibly producing polar cap patches (e.g., Carlson, 2012; Lockwood & Carlson, 1992; Wang et al., 2016; Zhang, Zhang, Moen, et al., 2013). Therefore, the appearance of patches on the southward IMF Bz in Figure 8c can be reasonably explained by the dayside magnetic reconnection.

Nevertheless, the less number of patches on the northward IMF Bz in Figure 8c could not be simply explained by the suppression effect from this speciﬁc IMF condition due to the natural bias raised by using the TEC keogram. Under the northward IMF Bz, the convection pattern would probably change into much variable cells rather than the uniform antisunward direction, which is frequently out of the observing direction of TEC keogram. Then, the possible patches generated under the northward IMF Bz are also not easily recorded by the TEC keogram.

Figure 9 shows the dependence of the average cross‐cap transit time of the detected patches on IMF conditions binned in 3‐nT intervals, (a) for IMF Bx, (b) for IMF By, and (c) for IMF Bz. The red lines represent the

WANG ET AL.

8 of 11

Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics

