mean cross‐cap transit times within each 3‐nT interval and blue bars represent their standard deviations. It is interesting to discuss the mean time in Figure 9c. When IMF Bz become stronger from −3 to −15 nT gradually, the average cross‐cap transit time decreases from ~2 to ~1.77 hr smoothly. In other words, the moving speed of the patches is likely controlled by the IMF Bz component, stronger the southward of IMF Bz faster the moving speed, which is not only consistent with the previous works (e.g., Hosokawa et al., 2006; Hosokawa, Shiokawa, et al., 2009) but also extends to the full polar cap. In addition, it is also a further proof to support the main role of magnetic reconnection on patch formation.

Figure 9. The dependence of average cross‐cap transit period of the detected
patches on IMF conditions binned in 3‐nT intervals, (a) IMF Bx, (b) IMF By, and (c) IMF Bz. The red lines indicate the average times of those patches within 3‐nT interval and blue bars correspond to their standard deviations.

Additionally, it is worth noting that in the statistical studies of patch occurrence, the state of motion of the patch through the full polar cap is conducted for the ﬁrst time in this paper. While earlier such studies were focusing on the patch density (e.g., Coley & Heelis, 1998; David et al., 2016; Jin et al., 2019; Moen et al., 2007, 2015; Ren et al., 2018; Sojka et al., 1994). Hence, our results from TEC keogram could in future answer further questions regarding the relationships between the patches and their background plasma convection.
6. Conclusions

Acknowledgments This research was supported by the National key R&D Program of China (2018YFC1407304, 2018YFC1407303), the National Natural Science Foundation of China (grants 41874170, 41574138, 41604139, 41774166, 41831072, 41431072), the Chinese Meridian Project, and the Specialized Research Funds of the National Key Laboratory of Electromagnetic Environment. The GPS TEC acquisition effort is led by A.J. Coster at MIT Haystack Observatory from worldwide network. We sincerely thank the MIT Haystack Observatory for processing GPS TEC data and making them available through the Madrigal Database (http://madrigal.haystack. mit.edu/). We also acknowledge the NASA OMNI Web for IMF and solar wind data (http://omniweb.gsfc.nasa. gov/html/sc_merge_data1.html), WDC C1, Kyoto for the AE/AL and SYM‐H indices (http://wdc.kugi.kyoto‐u.ac.jp/ wdc/Sec3.html). The effort of Virginia Tech. is very appreciated for providing SuperDARN radar data through website (http://vt.superdarn.org/tiki‐ index.php). SuperDARN is a collection of radars funded by national scientiﬁc funding agencies of Australia, Canada, China, France, Japan, South Africa, United Kingdom, and United States of America. SuperDARN RKN radar is run by the University of Saskatchewan.

In this paper, the development of a powerful tool named TEC keogram is presented. The TEC keogram is developed using the time series of TEC maps along three meridian TEC lines in 12–0 MLT, 15–3 MLT, and 9–21 MLT, respectively, all in the MLat ranges of 50°–90°N. This new tool (TEC keogram) is validated and its capability is demonstrated by comparing the large‐scale plasma structures in the polar ionosphere presented in the keograms with those in the original TEC maps and SuperDARN RKN radar observations. In addition, the statistics of the patch occurrences on months and UT hours obtained from TEC keogram agree well with those reported earlier from direct patch observations. The dependence of the patch occurrence on IMF conditions obtained using TEC keogram also agree with previous such studies using direct patch observation, which seems to conﬁrm that dayside magnetic reconnection is a factor involved in the generation of polar cap patches. TEC keogram technique is used for statistically studying the patch motion by considering the plasma movement relative to the background in the full polar cap for the ﬁrst time, which may probably answer further questions on their relationships in future.
However, this tool has some limitations. When the plasma structures drift along the selected TEC lines, the TEC keogram works very well. However, this condition is not always met due to the dynamic variation of the convection pattern. For example, in Figure 5a, the patches B/C are actually tongue of ionizations, which are moving toward the duskside. Unfortunately, they are beyond the detecting scope of the TEC line of 12–0 MLT because of the rapid northward pulsations of IMF Bz (Figure 3a). To overcome this limitation to some extend, three TEC lines have been employed in the TEC keogram, trying to accommodate the shifting of convection pattern better under highly dynamic IMF conditions. Moreover, the TEC data gap is also an inevitable problem especially in the polar region (e.g., patch E in Figure 5c), although the median ﬁlter has been applied to overcome this problem.
In short, proper use of the tool of TEC keogram can efﬁciently pre‐check and track the large‐scale irregularities in the polar ionosphere, instead of rushing into excessive TEC maps directly. Furthermore, the use of TEC keogram can support case studies and statistical studies of patch occurrence and its physical mechanism. Based on the development of this tool, the endeavor to fulﬁll the goals of automatic monitoring the large‐scale structures as well as estimating their size will be continued in the near future. An advancement to determine the patch velocity vector by combining multiple keograms will be carried as well.
